Bank Marketing Campaign Data Analysis¶

Data Description¶

The data is related with direct marketing campaigns of a banking institution. The marketing campaigns were based on phone calls. Often, more than one contact to the same client was required, in order to access if the product (bank term deposit) would be ('yes') or not ('no') subscribed.

Steps undertaken¶

1) Import the dataset and conduct a thorough analysis of the data present in the dataset. We look at the variables, observations, rows and columns. We are looking out for missing data, null value, missing rows that could affect the results of our analysis

2) Conduct data cleaning to remove irrelevant columns, missing rows, incorrect and missing values. We renamed the 'y' variable into 'deposit' to better represent our observations.

3) Conduct exploratory data analysis to detail our initial findings and results.

4) Provide further recommendations with regards to machine learning techniques to help predict the outcome of the direct marketing campaign. Further insights could be gained to help the marketing team determine which variables are important in determining if a client is willing to subscribe to a term deposit or not.

Distribution of Categorical Variables¶

In [10]:
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 80), dpi = 400)
plotnumber = 1
sns.set_theme(style='white')

for cat in cat_var:
    ax = plt.subplot(12, 3, plotnumber)
    sns.countplot(y=cat, data=df) 
    plt.ylabel(cat, fontsize = 14)
    plotnumber+=1

plt.show()

Takeaways¶

  • Majority of our clients holds management and blue-collar roles in their jobs. Students fall into the minority of our classification.
  • Majority of our clients are married while the minority are divorced.
  • Majority of our clients possess a secondary education.
  • Most of clients do not have credit card defaults, housing loans, and personal loans.
  • Most of our clients are contacted via cellular devices while the minority are telephones.
  • Most of our clients were last contacted in the month of May while the least were in Dec.
  • Most of the outcomes from our previous marketing campaign were unknown.

Distribution of Numerical Variables¶

In [78]:
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 80), dpi = 200)
sns.set_theme(style='white')
plotnumber = 1

for num in num_var:
    ax = plt.subplot(12, 3, plotnumber)
    sns.distplot(df[num])
    plt.xlabel(num, fontsize = 16)
    plotnumber+=1
    
plt.show()

Statistical Observations¶

  • The variables 'age' and 'day(last contact day of the month)' are normally distributed
  • Normal distribution: data is relatively symmetrical around the mean. Data near the mean occurs much more frequently as compared to those further away from the mean
  • There are possible outliers in all the other variables (balance, duration, campaign, pdays, previous)

Takeaways¶

  • Majority of bank clients lie between the age of 20 and 60

Boxplot of Numerical Variables¶

In [79]:
plt.figure(figsize=(20,80), dpi = 200)
sns.set_theme(style='white')
plotnumber =1

for num in num_var:
    ax = plt.subplot(12,3,plotnumber)
    sns.boxplot(x="deposit", y= df[num], data=df)
    plt.xlabel(num, fontsize = 16)
    plotnumber+=1
    
plt.show()

Takeaways¶

  • Box plots visually show the distribution of numerical data and skewness through displaying the data quartiles (or percentiles) and averages.
  • Presence of outliers is confirmed in the variables as follows: age, balance, duration, campaign, pdays, previous
  • The boxplot for duration seems to indicate that clients are more likely to subscribe to a term deposit the longer the last contact duration.

Further Recommendations¶

  • We could further proceed with Predictive Modelling to develop a classification model that is able to accurately predict if a client is willing to subscribe to a term deposit
  • We could make use of machine learning techniques such as Logistic Regression, K-Nearest Neighbors, Decision Tree, etc. to predict the outcome of this marketing campaign and find out important factors that directly affected the level of success achieved by the campaign
